comment_text: I feel like one of the most commonly missed portions of this conversation is regarding how hormone cycles and hormonal changes/responses are impacted by various hormonal birth controls, especially methods that obscure the menstrual cycle like Mirena. People with a uterus still experience hormonal fluctuations whether or not we ovulate, and I would love to hear a conversation that takes some of our most common prescription birth control methods into account. When trying to have conversations about hormones and ADHD, hormones and nutrition, hormones and sleep, hormones and training, hormones and mood, so much of the conversation revolves around when menstruation happens (never, if using long-term hormonal birth control like Mirena, Depo-Provera, etc.. ) or when ovulation occurs (never, if your hormonal birth control is doing its job). I would love to see more conversations that include the roughly 25%* of women (*in the US) who rely on various forms of hormonal birth control and perhaps cannot track their cycle through obvious indicators like bleeding.

video_title: Exercise & Nutrition Scientist: The Truth About Exercise On Your Period! Take These 4 Supplements!
comment_text: HRT has at least, evidence-based, effects on preventing osteoporosis. And there is some evidence that it helps longevity, quality of life, and prevent other diseases (including some cancers). Yes, women live longer, but they also live worse than men at older age. So, I think Dr. Sims' discussion on HRT is very limited. Fact is that we do not much more research because existing research is limited and does often not included newer forms of hormone therapies (e.g., transdermal versus oral) and start of HRT. So, saying that HRT is limited to bringing a women through the phase of menopause transition (considering also that a part of women will experience symptoms for the rest of their life) is frustrating. The current position of the menopause society is that HRT does not need to be limited to only a few years but can be continued as long as it helps. It is not a youth fountain, but it helped me personally a loss - including easing joint pain and giving more energy necessary to do all the exercises Dr. Sims' suggests.

video_title: Exercise & Nutrition Scientist: The Truth About Exercise On Your Period! Take These 4 Supplements!
comment_text:
At the beginning of last year, I came across this woman in a video, and her advice seemed compelling. I was entering perimenopause at the time, and her confidence inspired me to try following her recommendations. She advocated for high protein intake after workouts, creatine supplementation, and stopping fasting entirely. I followed her advice to the letter, but it didn’t work for me at all. Instead, it left me feeling worse—I gained weight, felt awful, and my energy levels plummeted.

This experience reminded me how important it is to find what works for your own body. While I respect her perspective, I decided to return to the practices that have transformed my life: ketogenic nutrition and fasting. I’m also a dietitian, and over the years, I’ve moved away from the standard American diet toward more natural approaches to health. Keto and fasting have been instrumental in improving my quality of life, and more recently, I’ve started exploring Ayurvedic nutrition, which is fascinating.

To be honest, my trust in her advice has declined over time. For example, in another video, she speaks with Dr. Mindy Pelz, a fasting advocate, and doesn’t disagree with her points. Yet, she’s been outspoken against fasting for people who engage in high-intensity sports, which creates an inconsistency in her messaging. Dr. Mindy promotes fasting as a tool for the general population of women, and from my own experience, I’ve found fasting to be a game-changer.

When I returned to fasting, my life improved significantly. I don’t agree with claims suggesting that fasting or keto can harm intestinal flora. In all my research—and I’ve done plenty—I’ve found the opposite to be true. Both fasting and keto have positive effects on gut health and metabolic function. There’s a lot of deep science behind this, but I’ll leave it at this: these practices are incredibly beneficial when done correctly.

I’ve also seen how individualized these approaches can be. My husband, who is an ultramarathoner, started keto three years ago. His performance has improved tremendously, though his version of keto includes more carbohydrates to fuel his high levels of activity. Keto is not a one-size-fits-all diet—it’s a flexible way of eating that can be adjusted to fit individual needs and lifestyles.

The same applies to fasting. It’s not just about skipping meals; it’s about understanding your body and tailoring your approach to suit your unique physiology. For me, keto and fasting aren’t just diets—they’re lifestyles that have improved my energy, strength, and overall well-being.

In summary, while I initially trusted this woman’s advice, my personal experience, research, and professional background have taught me otherwise. These tools—keto and fasting—are transformative, and I encourage anyone watching to explore what works best for them. Always listen to your body, do your own research, and trust what feels right for you.

comment_text: This is a well-known phenomenon in Psychology and not just because of menstrual cycles. Most psychometric tests were originally based on a young male sample, because in the 50s, there were few college women to recruit. This rubbish about not using women because of menstrual cycles still persists in psychophysiology as well. When many researchers do use women, they only use women with menstrual cycles that work like clockwork, which means we have very little understanding of women's bodies in general, but particularly women who may have hormonal imbalances etc, This is so much why women's health is so poorly informed and there is so little help for us. It was only recently discovered that women don't experience heart attacks the same way  - we have shoulder, arm and jaw pain, for example - so many women have died because they didn't show a male pattern of heart attack.

comment_text: 1:22:00 This is a great podcast so far, but she's misusing the word "spotting," conflating it with "light bleeding." Spotting refers to light bleeding that occurs outside of your regular menstrual period. Spotting can occur at any time during the menstrual cycle, often mid-cycle (around ovulation) or right before the period starts. On the other hand, light bleeding is part of your menstrual period and occurs during the expected time of menstruation, often at the beginning or end of your period.

comment_text:
For those short on time I summarized the transcript of the audio here:

The Female Physiology in Exercise

Key Differences: Women’s hormonal profiles—puberty, reproductive years, pregnancy, perimenopause, menopause—impact training and nutrition significantly.

Male-based research dominates sports science, often generalizing findings to women.

Girls often drop out of sports by age 14 due to physiological changes (e.g., Q angle, hip widening) and lack of guidance.

Impact of the Menstrual Cycle:

Follicular Phase (Day 1-13): Lower hormones; more resilient to stress, better glucose sensitivity. Ideal for high-intensity training.

Luteal Phase (Post-Ovulation): Progesterone rises; increased insulin resistance and core temperature. Focus on moderate training and recovery.

Progesterone and estrogen influence ligament laxity, increasing injury risk around ovulation.

Training and Injury Prevention

ACL Injuries in Women:

Women have a 3-4x higher risk due to wider hips (Q angle) and quad dominance.

Prevention: Strengthen the posterior chain (hamstrings, glutes) and incorporate lateral movements and single-leg exercises.

Resistance Training:

Essential across all ages for fat mobilization, muscle building, and improving metabolism.

Protein intake post-exercise: 35g for women (vs. 20g for men) within 45 minutes.

Heat and Cold Adaptation:

Women require more time in saunas for equivalent cardiovascular benefits.

Optimal cold plunge temperature: 15°C for women (vs. near-freezing for men).

Nutrition for Women

Fasting:

Women should avoid prolonged fasting (e.g., 20-hour fasts) due to hormonal sensitivity and metabolic impact.

Overnight fasting (dinner 2-3 hours before sleep, breakfast upon waking) is recommended.

Carbohydrates and Protein:

Women’s bodies require more carbohydrates to support hormonal and muscular functions, particularly during high hormone phases.

Pre-exercise fueling: 15g protein + 30g carbs to prevent lean mass loss.

Supplements:

Creatine: 3-5g daily for brain health, muscle performance, and gut integrity.

Vitamin D3: For muscle function, recovery, and overall health.

Omega-3: Particularly valuable for inflammation management in perimenopause/postmenopause.

Iron: Monitor and supplement if ferritin levels are below 50 (ideally 100 for active women).

Keto Diet:

Not recommended due to its negative impact on gut microbiome diversity, which is crucial for hormone metabolism.

Practical Takeaways

Adapting Training: Align workouts with menstrual phases for optimal performance and recovery.

Injury Prevention: Strengthen posterior chain and practice proper mechanics for landing, jumping, and cutting.

Dietary Adjustments: Tailor meals and supplements to hormonal fluctuations and individual needs.

Recovery Windows: Women’s metabolic recovery post-exercise is shorter; prioritize nutrient intake within 45 minutes.

Fasting: Focus on circadian-aligned eating patterns rather than prolonged fasting.

comment_text:
Thank you for inviting Dr. Stacy Sims!
I wanted to help out some of the fellow commentators asking: Why did keto work for me then? What about other experts contradicting Dr. Sims? Why does this and that work for me well, then? Her statements must be false. Scientific data and statistics give a insight on the population level. These are geralisations that do apply to the average yet not to every single individual. If you follow advice, if the science behind it was robust, it is likely it will help you (much more likely then science that was only based on men or was conducted with small sample sizes etc.) yet it is never a guarantee. Please note as well, that you might have underlying conditions, that make you react differently. Every body is unique in a way, and science tries to get as close as possible to the generalised population in this case, refreshingly the female part of it (or the forogtten other half). If other experts give contrary advice, please have a look at the literature they are basing their statements on. They might very well be based on males only or not underlined with scientific results at all. And then, sometimes it might be just so, that we do not yet have sufficient information to give a solid advice at all - then go and try that suits you best.  

Good luck and health!

comment_text:
As a women in mensapuse, here's my take:

- Women often find typical fitness and dietary plans ineffective due to unique physiological changes across their life stages.
- Dr. Stacy Sims advocates for personalized fitness and nutrition strategies tailored for women, addressing the shortcomings of male-based sports science data.
- Puberty brings physical changes that affect girls' participation in sports, with a significant dropout rate by age 14 due to lack of tailored support.
- Tailored exercise and nutrition plans can enhance women's health and performance by factoring in menstrual cycle variations and hormonal changes.
- Menopause introduces challenges like weight gain and muscle loss, requiring a focus on resistance training and adequate protein intake.
- Misunderstandings about diets and supplements are addressed, promoting evidence-based approaches for women's health.
- Research and advocacy are closing the gender gap in sports science, empowering women to make informed health and fitness choices.

Summary by megasummary.com

video_title: Exercise & Nutrition Scientist: The Truth About Exercise On Your Period! Take These 4 Supplements!
comment_text: I learned a lot from this episode, but when she said hormone therapy was a last resort, should be taken at a low dose, suggested that it was only meant to help through the transition, and things get better “on the other side,” she lost me. “On the other side,” women have no estrogen (or very, very little) in their bodies, putting us at higher risk for heart disease, osteoporosis and hip fracture, colon cancer, brain issues (see The Menopause Brain by Dr Lisa Mosconi) and who knows how many other maladies, for the rest of our lives. The debilitating symptoms of estrogen depletion such as urogenital and musculoskeletal issues, and so many more, do not just miraculously resolve at a certain point. (Surely she’s aware of Estrogen Matters by Dr. Avrum Blumming.) Replacing the missing estrogen is like replacing missing thyroid hormone, which nobody seems to have a problem with. The fact that she was associated with investigators on the WHI and didn’t make a point of how the results of that study were misreported, overblown, do not apply to younger women and involved synthetic hormones that aren’t even prescribed anymore is enough to make me doubt all the other truly interesting information she shared. Women do not use HRT to try to look like they aren’t aging. That is an old assumption that contributed to the misrepresentation of the WHI study data. We use HRT to feel like ourselves and be able to live as functionally, productively and happily as possible in the final third of our lives. There are great docs on social media like Mary Clair Haver, Corrine Menn, Vonda Wright, Louise Newson, and Kelly Casperson who provide truly valuable and up-to-date information for menopausal women. As far as hormones go, this guest did not do that.

**Key Insights: The Truth About Exercise, Nutrition, and Women’s Physiology**

#### 1. **Women’s Physiology is Unique and Often Overlooked**
   - Traditional sports science research has predominantly focused on male physiology, leading to generalized recommendations that often fail to address women’s unique needs. Women experience hormonal fluctuations throughout their lives—puberty, menstruation, pregnancy, perimenopause, and menopause—which significantly impact their fitness, metabolism, and overall health.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Women are not smaller versions of men. Their physiological differences, such as hormone profiles, muscle morphology, and fat distribution, require tailored approaches to exercise, nutrition, and recovery.

#### 2. **Hormonal Fluctuations Impact Exercise and Nutrition**
   - The menstrual cycle plays a critical role in how women respond to exercise and nutrition. For example:
     - **Follicular Phase (Days 1-14)**: Women are more resilient to stress and can handle higher-intensity workouts. Carbohydrate and protein intake can be higher without adverse effects.
     - **Luteal Phase (Days 15-28)**: Progesterone levels rise, increasing core temperature and reducing heat tolerance. Women may need more carbohydrates and protein to support energy needs and recovery.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Adapting exercise and nutrition to the menstrual cycle can optimize performance, recovery, and overall health.

#### 3. **Supplements for Women’s Health**
   - Certain supplements can support women’s health, especially during menstruation and menopause:
     - **Creatine**: Improves muscle performance, brain health, and gut integrity. Women have lower creatine stores than men and can benefit from 3-5 grams daily.
     - **Vitamin D3**: Essential for bone health, muscle function, and recovery, especially in winter or for those with limited sun exposure.
     - **Omega-3s**: Reduce inflammation and support cellular integrity, particularly during peri- and post-menopause.
     - **Iron**: Many women are iron-deficient, which can lead to fatigue and poor performance. Supplementing with high-bioavailability iron can improve energy levels and oxygen-carrying capacity.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Targeted supplementation can address common deficiencies and support women’s unique physiological needs.

#### 4. **Exercise Adaptations for Women**
   - Women’s bodies respond differently to exercise due to factors like muscle fiber composition, Q-angle (hip-knee alignment), and hormonal influences:
     - **Strength Training**: Women can build lower-body strength as effectively as men but may struggle with upper-body strength due to differences in muscle morphology.
     - **ACL Injury Prevention**: Women are 3-4 times more likely to suffer ACL injuries due to wider hips, quad dominance, and hormonal influences. Strengthening the posterior chain (hamstrings, glutes) and incorporating lateral movement exercises can reduce injury risk.
     - **Heat Acclimatization**: Women’s heat tolerance varies with their menstrual cycle. During the high-hormone phase, they may need more time to acclimatize to heat.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Women should focus on strength training, injury prevention, and adapting exercise intensity to their hormonal cycle.

#### 5. **Nutritional Differences Between Men and Women**
   - Women’s nutritional needs differ significantly from men’s due to hormonal influences and metabolic differences:
     - **Caloric Needs**: Women’s hypothalamuses are more sensitive to nutrient density, making them less responsive to low-calorie or low-carb diets. Fasted training can be detrimental, leading to muscle loss and hormonal dysfunction.
     - **Protein Timing**: Women should consume protein (35 grams) within 45 minutes post-exercise to maximize muscle protein synthesis, while men have a longer recovery window.
     - **Keto Diet**: Not recommended for women due to its negative impact on gut microbiome diversity, which is crucial for hormone metabolism and overall health.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Women should prioritize nutrient-dense diets, avoid fasting, and time protein intake to support recovery and hormonal balance.

#### 6. **Menopause and Perimenopause: A Critical Phase**
   - Perimenopause (starting around age 35) and menopause (average age 52) bring significant hormonal changes that affect metabolism, body composition, and overall health:
     - **Symptoms**: Increased body fat, poor sleep, mood changes, and insulin resistance are common. Women may also experience a decline in gut microbiome diversity and bone density.
     - **Exercise Recommendations**: High-intensity interval training (HIIT) and resistance training are crucial for maintaining muscle mass, improving insulin sensitivity, and managing weight.
     - **Nutrition**: Higher protein intake (1.6-2.2 grams per kg of body weight) is recommended to counteract anabolic resistance and support muscle and bone health.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Women in perimenopause and menopause should focus on high-intensity exercise, increased protein intake, and gut health to manage symptoms and maintain quality of life.

#### 7. **The Importance of Bone Health**
   - Women are at higher risk of osteoporosis due to hormonal changes that affect bone density. Resistance training, weight-bearing exercises, and adequate vitamin D intake are essential for maintaining bone health.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Strength training and proper nutrition are critical for preventing bone loss and reducing the risk of fractures, especially during and after menopause.

#### 8. **Sleep and Circadian Rhythms**
   - Women experience more sleep disruptions due to hormonal fluctuations, particularly during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle and perimenopause. Men, on the other hand, have a later melatonin peak and are less affected by hormonal changes.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Women should prioritize sleep hygiene and consider adjusting their routines to align with their circadian rhythms, especially during hormonal shifts.

#### 9. **Sociocultural Barriers and Lack of Education**
   - Women’s health topics, such as menstruation, menopause, and hormonal health, are often stigmatized or overlooked in education and healthcare. This lack of awareness can lead to misdiagnosis, inadequate treatment, and unnecessary suffering.
   - **Key Takeaway**: Open conversations and education about women’s health are essential for empowering women to take control of their health and well-being.

### Conclusion
Understanding the unique physiological and hormonal differences between men and women is crucial for optimizing health, fitness, and performance. Women’s bodies are not simply smaller versions of men’s; they require tailored approaches to exercise, nutrition, and recovery that account for hormonal fluctuations, life stages, and specific health challenges. By adapting exercise routines, prioritizing nutrient-dense diets, and addressing common deficiencies, women can achieve better health outcomes and improve their quality of life. Additionally, breaking down sociocultural barriers and increasing education about women’s health will empower women to make informed decisions and advocate for their well-being. Ultimately, embracing these insights can lead to a more inclusive and effective approach to health and fitness for women at every stage of life.

When training during different phases of the menstrual cycle, women should consider specific adaptations to optimize their performance and recovery.

Strength and Performance: Women tend to be strongest during the follicular phase, particularly from around day 6 to day 13 of the cycle, when estrogen levels begin to rise. This is an ideal time for higher intensity and resistance training as the body is more capable of handling stress and performing at peak levels 39.

Stress and Recovery: It's important to monitor stress levels, as both physical and emotional stress can impact the menstrual cycle. A missed period can indicate that the body is under stress, which may be due to excessive training or other life stressors. Therefore, adjusting training intensity and incorporating recovery strategies is crucial 40.

PCOS Considerations: For women with conditions like PCOS, focusing on resistance training can help regulate cycles and manage symptoms. It's essential to monitor heart rate variability and adjust training intensity accordingly to support blood glucose levels and overall well-being 41.

By aligning training with these physiological changes, women can enhance their performance and maintain better overall health throughout their menstrual cycle.

comment_text: Bioidentical hormone treatment is exactly what is needed. Do not be afraid of the hormones. We need them, Estrogen protects our brain, skin, bones…the key is to not use synthetic versions. Stay away from Premarin and Progestins. Bioidentical estrogen like the patch or pellets are the right choices. Real progesterone at night will help with sleep. Testosterone helps us not to lose strength, energy, and libido and just feel better overall. I’m 61 and been on this road awhile. It takes time to learn your body and the best dosages for optimal health. Stay away from a dr that wants to limit estrogen or will only give the estrogen pill. The pill is not assimilated well and will eventually not be enough. FSH on lab work tells about estrogen. Best is under 10. Optimal is under 5. I’ve done tons of reading and studying. If the dr says Estrogen is given at the lowest dose and shortest amount of time then find another dr. I get pellets. I was at one dr that wanted to give Testosterone at doses like 125mg which they say is low but that’s way too high for me. He would not give Estrogen over 18mg. I found another dr. I now usually get about 25-30mg Estrogen and 65-85 Testosterone. Everyone is different. I will never stop taking my bioidentical hormones. There is help out there. Insurance isn’t going to pay for much so don’t expect it. I pay $350. every 3-4 months for pellets. Progesterone is about $30. per bottle but I don’t take it every night because it can make me feel sluggish during the day if it builds up too much. I also take desicated thyroid called NP Thyroid. It is a prescription. It is a balancing act also. If estrogen is higher then my dose of thyroid will be higher.  My dr and I are a team. She trusts me to make decisions on dosages and she gives her advice. A good Dr will listen and think outside the box. Learn to read your own body.

comment_text:
The four recommended supplements. Please read my additional notes at the end.

• Creatine:

Ideal daily dose: 3-5 grams once daily for maintenance.

Loading phase: Some people choose to do a "loading phase" when starting creatine supplementation to saturate their muscle stores more quickly. This typically involves taking 20 grams of creatine per day (divided into 4 servings of 5 grams each) for 5-7 days. After the loading phase, you return to the maintenance dose of 3-5 grams per day.

Best form: Creatine monohydrate.

Worst form: Creatine ethyl ester.

Men vs. women: Both benefit; women may see enhanced benefits during perimenopause/menopause.

How Creatine Helps:

ATP Production: Creatine plays a crucial role in the production of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), the primary energy source for muscle contractions. During high-intensity exercise, ATP is rapidly depleted. Creatine helps replenish ATP by donating a phosphate molecule to ADP (adenosine diphosphate), converting it back to ATP. This allows you to maintain high-intensity effort for a slightly longer duration.

• Vitamin D3:

Ideal daily dose: This is where location matters. Here's a breakdown based on general recommendations.

Warmer climates (e.g., Southern Europe, Australia): 600-1000 IU (15-25 mcg) daily may be sufficient for most people with regular sun exposure.

Colder climates (e.g., Northern Europe, Canada): 1000-2000 IU (25-50 mcg) daily is often recommended due to less sun exposure, especially during winter months.

For deficiency or specific conditions: Higher doses (up to 4000 IU or more) may be prescribed by a doctor to correct a deficiency or manage certain health conditions.

Best form: Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is the preferred form as it's more effective at raising vitamin D levels than D2.

Worst form: Vitamin D2 (ergocalciferol) is generally less effective.

Men vs. women: Both men and women need vitamin D. Women may have increased needs during pregnancy and breastfeeding, and adequate vitamin D levels are crucial for bone health throughout a woman's life.

• Omega-3s:

Ideal daily dose: Leading experts often recommend a combined EPA and DHA intake of at least 250-500 mg per day for general health. Higher doses (1000-2000 mg or more) may be recommended for specific conditions like cardiovascular health or managing inflammation.

Dietary Choices: People who consume fatty fish (salmon, mackerel, sardines) 2-3 times per week may obtain sufficient omega-3s from their diet. Vegetarians and vegans may need to rely on algae-based EPA/DHA supplements.

Best Form:

EPA and DHA Content: The most crucial factor is the amount of EPA (eicosapentaenoic acid) and DHA (docosahexaenoic acid) in the supplement. These are the primary omega-3 fatty acids with the most significant health benefits. Check the supplement label for the combined EPA and DHA content per serving, not just the total fish oil or omega-3 content.

Triglyceride (TG) Form: Omega-3s in their natural triglyceride form are generally considered to have better bioavailability (absorption) than ethyl ester (EE) forms. Look for "TG" or "natural triglyceride" on the label.

Phospholipid Form: Krill oil and some other specialized omega-3 supplements contain omega-3s bound to phospholipids. These may also offer enhanced absorption, although more research is needed to confirm if they are significantly superior to TG forms. They are generally more expensive.

Purity and Testing: Choose supplements from reputable brands that undergo third-party testing for purity and contaminants like mercury, PCBs, and dioxins. Look for certifications from organizations like the USP (United States Pharmacopeia) or NSF International.

Sustainability: Consider the source of the omega-3s. Look for certifications from organizations like the Marine Stewardship Council (MSC) to ensure the fish oil is sourced sustainably.

Worst Form: 

Oxidized or Rancid Oil: Omega-3 fatty acids are prone to oxidation (rancidity), which can reduce their effectiveness and even produce harmful compounds. Avoid supplements that smell fishy or have an unpleasant odour. Look for products packaged in dark, opaque bottles and stored in a cool, dark place.

Low EPA/DHA Content: Some supplements may advertise high total omega-3 content but contain very low amounts of EPA and DHA. Pay close attention to the specific EPA and DHA values on the label.

Ethyl Ester (EE) Form (Less Ideal): While not inherently "bad," ethyl ester forms are less readily absorbed than triglyceride forms. If you choose an EE supplement, consider taking it with a meal containing fat to improve absorption.

Unclear Sourcing/Lack of Testing: Avoid supplements from brands that don't disclose their sourcing or don't perform third-party testing.

Men vs. women: Both men and women benefit from omega-3s. Women may find them particularly helpful during perimenopause to address inflammation and mood changes.

• Iron:

Ideal daily dose: This varies significantly based on individual needs and iron status. General recommendations for adults are around 8mg for men and 18mg for pre-menopausal women. However, active women, those with heavy menstrual bleeding, or those diagnosed with iron deficiency may need significantly higher doses.

Enhancing Absorption: Vitamin C significantly enhances non-heme iron absorption (found in plant-based foods). Consuming iron-rich foods with vitamin C-rich foods (citrus fruits, bell peppers) can improve iron intake.

Inhibiting Absorption: Certain substances can inhibit iron absorption, including calcium, tannins (found in tea and coffee), and phytates (found in grains and legumes). It's best to avoid consuming these substances with iron-rich foods or supplements.

Best form: Carbonyl or glycinate iron are highly bioavailable and well-tolerated forms.

Worst form: Ferrous sulfate is a common but less bioavailable form and may cause gastrointestinal issues.

Men vs. women: Women generally have higher iron needs than men due to menstruation. Active women and those with heavy menstrual bleeding may require even more iron.

Additional points about Omega 3, Iron, and Creatine:

Omega 6: A high intake of omega-6 fatty acids (found in many processed foods and vegetable oils) can compete with omega-3s for absorption and utilization. Balancing omega-6 intake is important for maximizing the benefits of omega-3 supplementation.

Iron Testing: It's essential to get your iron levels checked by a doctor before starting iron supplementation. Iron overload can be harmful.

Creating Loading: A loading phase is not strictly necessary. Taking the maintenance dose of 3-5 grams per day will still saturate your muscle stores, but it will take about 3-4 weeks to achieve the same level of saturation as with a loading phase.

Yet in an interview on this very podcast - Dr Mindy repeated that exercising fasted is beneficial for women (she even has a short of it on her FB page) so I’m leaning more towards Dr Mindy Pelz giving out contradictory messaging around this but she is emphatic on the benefits of fasted training for women where Dr Simms isn’t.

video_title: Exercise & Nutrition Scientist: The Truth About Exercise On Your Period! Take These 4 Supplements!
comment_text:
It is more challenging with your condition to do certain things, but not to be healthy. Your definition of healthy needs to be broader. Excercise is just 1 pillar. With your condition or even in a normal person health can be Excercise, diet, sleep and stress management. 
Even if you find it difficult to do workouts that's fine. Can you sleep for 8 hours? Can you have a consistent sleep and wake time e.g. 11pm-7am?  This is a huge part of our healthy life. 
Food - can you make sure you drink 2L of water a day? Cut out caffine or a least minimise to no more than 2 cups of coffee? No coffee after 3pm. Can you cut out processed foods? Eg sugar snacks, crisps, cereals etc. Can you increase your vegetables intake? Can you increase your lean protein intake? Can you have healthy fats in yout diet and avoid seed oil? Can you stop alcohol? 
Stress-  Can you spend 5 mins a day meditating? Can you spend 5 mins journalling? 
Excercise- can you go for 10 min walk outside daily? 
Can you do 5 body weight squats while you are making a cup of tea in the morning and waiting for the kettle to boil. 
Can you get 2x 1kg weights and practice arm raises and bicep curls? 
I'm saying this to be kind as I care for someone with a health issue, and I myself know what its like to have a self limiting belief. Its not all or nothing, you dont need a personal trainer, most of them don't know how to adapt to different abilities, you can be healthy in so many ways, even if you can't do intense Excercise, some of the things ive listed above are so easy for someone even in your condition. Just try different things and don't give up
